The paper discusses deterministic parallel algorithms for combinatorial optimization problems, which are typically studied in the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The use of conditional expectations and probability spaces with low independence suggests a connection to randomized algorithms, which are often studied in the sub-category of cs.CC (Computational Complexity). The paper also mentions applications to discrepancy, which is a topic in the sub-category of cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The algorithms for maximum acyclic subgraph and Gale-Berlekamp switching games suggest a connection to graph theory and computational geometry, which are studied in the sub-categories of cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis), respectively.
